ntsb3046txt-1-5-5-0-4 The right magnetos were also checked with no obvious malfunctions noted. 
ntsb3046txt-1-5-5-0-10 He flew the airplane until terrain clearance was no longer possible, then landed in a field, gear up. 
ntsb3046txt-1-5-5-0-5 A descent for landing was initiated to the Tri-City airport and manifold heat was applied and removed several times, with no appreciable effect. 
ntsb3046txt-1-5-5-0-11 The airplane slid into trees and was substantially damaged. 
ntsb3046txt-1-5-5-0-8 A go-around was initiated, during which the pilot discovered that the left manifold heat control was now stuck in the 'ON' position. 
ntsb3046txt-1-5-5-0-3 Right engine manifold heat was applied for a few seconds, with no noticeable difference in engine performance. 
ntsb3046txt-1-5-5-0-7 There was insufficient time to perform the emergency gear extension procedure. 
ntsb3046txt-1-5-5-0-9 The pilot stated that with less than full power available on the left engine, and the right propeller unfeathered, the airplane could be climbed to about 200 feet. 
ntsb3046txt-1-5-5-0-2 The airplane was in the clouds with an outside air temperature of about zero degrees Celsius. 
ntsb3046txt-1-5-5-0-6 On short final approach, when the landing gear was extended, the right main gear did not indicate down. 
ntsb3046txt-1-5-5-0-1 The pilot reported that as he overflew the Tri-City airport, Tennessee at 9,000 feet, the right engine power slowly decreased. 
